{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_kale_ver01/data/2017236974/00279558078/1945092001/0856.xml":{"full_text":"CANADA DEVELOPS HER ELECTRIC POWER\ni -^1 A At A T\"\\ A t i,i m _ __\n1 iptANADA has a wealth of water\nVv power resources favorably dis\nj trlbuted throughout the country in\n1 relation to other natural resources,\nto centers of population and to\ntransportation facilities. Since the\nturn of the present century, water\npower development has had a pro\nfound effect upon the national\n'economy. This development, in\ncreasing from a total of 173,000 h.p.\nIn 1900 to more than 10,283.000 h.p.\nIn 1944, has been the mainspring\nof the great industrial expansion\nof the past four decades and has\nbrought to the greater part of the\npopulation the amenities of electric\nlighting and other electric services.\nIn the past five years of war, water\npower has been fundamental to\nCanada\u2019s vast war production pro\ngram. Aluminum production alone,\nwhich has increased sixfold since\n1939, has taken latterly one-quarter\nof all electric energy generated in\nthe Dominion and power has per\nformed a vital role in virtually\nevery phase of the war effort In\nthe post-war period, Canada\u2019s re\nsources of developed and undevel\noped water power will be of strate\ngic assistance in meeting the prob\nlems of reconstruction and rehabili\ntation.\nAs it has proven sound commer\ncial practice to install hydraulic\npower equipment averaging 30 p.c.\ntn excess of the six-month flow\npower, it is estimated that Canada\u2019s\npresently recorded water power\nprovides for an installation of more\nthan 51,350,000 h.p. That is. the\npresent development represents\nonly 20 p.c. of the possible devel\nopment\nUp to 1943 the pulp and paper\nindustry was the largest consumer\nof electricity but because of a sub\nstitution of coal for electricity in\nUs boilers its total consumption\nwas almost 2.000.000.000 kilowatt\nhours less in 1943 than in 1939.\ndespite an increase of more than F\n1.000.000.000 kw h of primary pow- F\ner. In 1943 it was surpassed by the F\naluminum industry as a consumer, f\nCanada\u2019s \u201cwhite coal,\" the Niagara River (top), cascades through its\ngourge to the mighty Niagara Falls is one of their important sources of\npower. (Lower right) A huge generator is shown being carefully drop\nped Into position at Unit #10, Shipshaw. (Lower left) Workmen put the\nfinal touches on the dam at Barrett\u2019s Chute.\nSOCIAL SECURITY\nDon\u2019t Confuse Federal Old-Age And Survivors Insurance With\nUnemployment Insurance\nEvery once in a while a worker\ncomes stomping into a local office\nof the Social Security Board mad\nto the gills.\n\u201cSee here,\u201d he says, \u201cI\u2019ve been out\nof a job for five weeks and they\nwon\u2019t give me my unemployment\ninsurance. \u201cI\u2019ve been paying my\nsocial security right along and now\nwhen I need my compensation I\ncan\u2019t get it.\u201d\nThe Social Seurity Board\u2019s field\noffice may not be able to tell him\nwhy he don\u2019t get unemployment in\nsurance, since the local office do\nesn\u2019t administer this program. May\nbe the reason is that he hadn\u2019t\nworked long enough in covered jobs\nto become insured. Maybe it\u2019s be\ncause he quit his job voluntarily or\nbecause he was unable to work or\nsome other reason. But the Board\ndoes tell him he\u2019s got the two social\ninsurance programs all mixed up\nunemployment insurance with old\nage and surivors insurance. And it\nstraightens him out.\nUnemployment insurance is a\nState program. Each State has its\nown unemployment insurance law\nand each State runs its own pro\ngram. To draw benfits a worker\nmust be injured under the\nstate law. That\u2019s the frist thing.\nOver and above that, he must in\ngeneral have (1) registered for\nwork at a public employment office\nand filed his claim for benefits; (2)\nhe must have been working on a\ncovered jobs; (3) he must be avai\nlable for work and able to work.\nExcept in the State of Rhode Is\nland, he can\u2019t get unemployment\nbenefits if he is sick.\nNow as to paying. Except in Ala\nbama, California, New Jersey, and\nRhode Island, workers *don\u2019t help\npay unemployment insurance. In all\nStates except these four, employers\ndo all the paying for unemployment\ninsurance. The one percent deduc\ntion from your pay for social se\ncurity is not for unemployment in\nsurance. It is for old-age and survi\nvors insurance.\nThis insurance system is a Fed\neral program run by the Federal\nGovernment. The Social Security\nBoards keeps the records and pass- i\nes upon the claims. The U. S. Trea\nsury collects the social security tax\nes and pays out the benefit checks.\nYou cannot get unemployment in\nsurance benefits out of old-age and\nsurvivors insurance. The purpose of\nthis program is to provided month\nly benefits for you and your family\nwhen you are 65 or more and retire\nand for your family when you die.\nThe two programs are entirely\nseparate. You can no more get un\nemployment benefits from the So\ncial Security Board than you can\nbuy fish in a shoe store. If you lose\nyour job, don\u2019t go to the Social Se\ncurity Board field office unless you\nare 65. Go straight to the nearest\nU. S. Employment Office and re\ngister for a job. At the same time\nand in the same place file your cl\naim. If you qualify under the law\nof your state, after a short waiting\nperiod one or two weeks you will\nget your unemployment benefits,\nprovided you are still unemployed.\nThe Social Security Board office\nwhich serves this territory is loca\n;ed in the Post Office Building in\nRocky Mount, N. C.\nA representative of the Rocky\nMount office will be in Roanoke\nRapids at the Employment office\neach 1st and 3rd Tuesday at 2:00\np. m.\nThe Norwegians built guns, de\nspite watchful Nazis, by dividing\nthe parts to a factory and as\nsembling them in a forest. What\u2019s\nto hinder the Germans doing it?\nL. S. (Pete)\nGARNER\nGENERAL\nCONTRACTOR\nAND\nBUILDER\nPlans and\nEstimates Furnished\nGood Work at\nA Reasonable Price\nPhone R-884-6\n701 Vance St.\n...J\nFINAL NOTICE-PULLETS\n\nWe have only 450 New Hampshire Pullets\nleft. Best quality. Will start laying in October.4*1\nMust be sold by September 22, to make\nroom for new flocks.\nWeight about 3 lbs. Price 50c per lb.\n\nROANOKE CHICKEN RANCH'\nBOLLING ROAD PHONE: R-6322\n1\nI WHEN YOUR property\nis damaged, it is very\nI comforting to call your\ninsurance agent and\nhear him say:\u2014\n\u201cYour policy covers\ni; that loss. I\u2019ll be right\nover\u201d\nAsk\" this Hartford\nagency to plan your in\nsurance to cover losses\nto which you individual-\nly are likely to be sub-\njected.\nNATIONAL\nLOAN INSURANCE CO.. INC*\n12 W. Second St. Dial R-444-1 I\nREDDY KILOWATT Knots to You VIRGINIA ELECTRIC POWER CO.\u00ab\nAnother\u2019ELECTRIC\nfcu TIE A KNOT IN THIS]\n-HANDKERCHIEF WITHOUT LETTIN6/\n60 OF THE, M\nENDS. y\nGIVE UP/WILLIE? WELL,\nOUST FOLD VOUR ARMS\nAND PICK UP\nONE END\nLIKE THIS\nDON'T\nLET 60\nOF THE\nCORNERS\n\nmmsmm\nWWWWBWWWWfP\u2014 UI\nSPEAKING of KNOTS\"\nIF YOUR IRON CORO LOOKS\nLIKE THIS FIXIT! OR\nIT MAY CAUSE TROUBLE.","height":"21840","width":"14460"}}
